*From this research, I see that the traditional view of the "forgetting curve" oversimplifies the challenge of knowledge retention. It focuses on what learners forget over time, rather than how to ensure they retain and recall information as needed.*

*The key principles of learning science, cited by Halpern and Hakel, suggest that focusing on "practice at retrieval" is more useful - asking learners to respond to cues and practice retrieving information. This turns the forgetting curve into a retention strategy.*

*An effective knowledge retention strategy should aim to:*

*1) Ensure that learners can actively recall and apply information in the appropriate context, not just focus on what they've forgotten over time.*

