3. Efficiency - MoE models can be more parameter-efficient than dense models by using fewer parameters for each sub-task. This allows them to be more scalable and deployable in resource-constrained environments. For example, GPT-OSS(20B/120B) uses only 20B parameters for a 120B model by activating only a subset of its experts.

4. Improved performance - MoE models often outperform dense models by leveraging their specialized experts and efficient routing. For instance, GPT-OSS(20B/120B) achieves better performance than LLaMA-70b on various benchmarks while using only a fraction of the parameters.

5. Flexibility - MoE models can be easily adapted to different tasks or domains by modifying the set of experts or the routing signal. This allows them to be more versatile and adaptable than dense models like Hermes-3, which require retraining or fine-tuning to adapt to new tasks.

