  📤 → User: As I reflect on the question "How do LoRA fine-tuning runs work — what will happen when my experience_tuples.jsonl hits 500 and training/lora_trigger.py fires?" and explore the concept of LoRA fine-tuning, I recognize that there are several key aspects to consider. One important aspect is the comparison between traditional fine-tuning and LoRA (Low-Rank Adaptation). Traditional fine-tuning involves updating all or a significant portion of a pre-trained model's parameters, which can be computationally intensive and resource-demanding. In contrast, LoRA is a parameter-efficient technique that introduces small trainable matrices into certain layers, allowing most of the original model parameters to remain unchanged. This approach drastically reduces memory and compute requirements, making LoRA much faster and more efficient than full fine-tuning, especially for large language models, while still achieving comparable performance on many tasks.

