  📤 → User: As I reflect on the question "How do mixture-of-experts models compare to a single dense model like Hermes-3?" and explore the comparison between dense models and mixture of experts (MoE) models, I recognize that there are several key aspects to consider. One important aspect is the difference in how these models activate parameters for every token. Dense models activate every parameter for every token, resulting in simple and predictable scaling in compute and memory. In contrast, MoE models activate only a subset of parameters per token, resulting in massive total parameter counts at lower active compute, but with memory, communication, and training stability trade-offs.

Another key aspect is the rule of thumb that an 8-way sparse model has inference economics roughly equivalent to a dense model half its total size, not its active size, and certainly not its full size. This suggests that MoE models can be more efficient in terms of inference economics compared to dense models with the same total parameter count.

