  📤 → User: As I reflect on the question "How do mixture-of-experts models compare to a single dense model like Hermes-3?" and explore the latest research on mixture-of-experts models, I recognize that there are several key aspects to consider. One notable aspect is the comparison between dense models and mixture-of-experts models in terms of their architecture, computation, and inference. Dense models use the same set of parameters for every input, while mixture-of-experts models route each input to a small subset of specialized expert networks, resulting in sparse activation and a larger total number of parameters.

