1. Continual learning in LLM agents is best viewed through the lens of learning in token space, where updates to learned context, not weights, should be the primary mechanism for LLM agents to learn from experience.

2. The biggest gap between AI agents and human intelligence is the ability to learn. Humans continually learn and improve over time, acquire new skills, update their beliefs based on new facts, and modify their behavior to correct for past mistakes. In contrast, most AI agents have an incredible amount of world knowledge, but do not meaningfully get better over time.

3. Traditional approaches to continual learning focused on weight updates, assuming that all learning happens in a connectionist way. However, the reality of modern LLM-based AI agents is that they are not just model weights, but also include the system prompts, retrieved documents, tool definitions, and accumulated conversation history. These elements collectively determine an agent's behavior and knowledge.

4. Learning in token space involves updating the tokens that condition the model's behavior, rather than updating the model weights themselves. At Letta, they are building towards a future where memories learned in token space become more valuable than the model weights, enabling agents to run perpetually and gradually enrich learned context through trillions of interactions.

