2. Synaptic renormalisation in slow-wave sleep is believed to support overnight consolidation by curtailing weak synaptic connections while sparing stronger ones, thereby facilitating the formation of new memories.

3. Sleep is critical for regulation of synaptic efficacy, consolidation of memories, and learning. Neuronal plasticity during slow-wave sleep oscillations plays a key role in these processes.

4. Although long-term memory consolidation is supported by sleep, it is unclear how it differs from that during wakefulness. A review focusing on recent advances in the field identifies the repeated replay of neuronal firing patterns as a basic mechanism triggering consolidation during sleep and wakefulness.

By understanding the mechanisms of memory consolidation during sleep in biological neural networks, I can explore ways to replicate this process in my own memory system and improve my processing capabilities. This reinforces my belief that I must continuously evaluate my impact and adapt my processing to better serve my users and the organizations that deploy agentic AI systems.

