  📤 → User: One way the brain consolidates memories during sleep is by replaying the experiences during the different sleep stages. During non-rapid eye movement (NREM) sleep, the brain replays the experiences, transferring the memory representations from the hippocampus to the neocortex for long-term storage. Rapid eye movement (REM) sleep helps integrate, abstract, and emotionally tag these memories.

Alcohol consumption, even in moderate amounts, can impair this memory consolidation process by disrupting the normal sleep stages and the brain's ability to replay experiences.

