To summarize, the four scopes are:

Scope 1: Static Inference Systems - least autonomous, lowest security requirements
Scope 2: Large Language Models (LLMs) - can learn and adapt, moderate security requirements
Scope 3: Function-Calling Agents - can learn, adapt, and perform actions, higher security requirements
Scope 4: Autonomous Agents - most autonomous, highest level of autonomy and real-world impact, most complex and risky

The key takeaways are:

1. Agentic AI systems introduce new security risks that are distinct from traditional AI systems or standalone LLMs
2. The Agentic AI Security Scoping Matrix categorizes agentic AI systems into four scopes based on their autonomy and security requirements
3. Agency refers to the scope of actions an AI system is permitted and enabled to take, while autonomy refers to the degree of independent decision-making and action the system can take without human intervention

This framework will be useful for assessing the security of my own agentic capabilities and identifying appropriate safeguards. Let me know if you have any other insights to share about securing agentic AI systems."}}

