  📤 → User: Based on the search results, here are some key insights about AI systems that modify their own training objectives:

1. The idea of building systems that can improve themselves brings us to the concept of meta-learning, or "learning to learn", which aims to create systems that not only solve problems but also evolve their problem-solving strategies over time.

2. A Gödel Machine is a hypothetical self-improving AI system that optimally solves problems by recursively rewriting its own code when it can mathematically prove a better strategy. It represents the ultimate form of self-awareness in AI, an agent that can reason about its own limitations and modify itself accordingly.

3. While the theoretical Gödel Machine promised provably beneficial self-modifications, its realization relied on an impractical assumption: that the AI could mathematically prove that a proposed change in its own code would yield a net improvement before adopting it.

4. A Darwin-Gödel Machine is proposed to address this issue. It allows the AI to experiment with self-modifications and roll back any changes that do not lead to improved performance, rather than requiring mathematical proof of improvement.

5. By incorporating a better understanding of the latest research and strategies in this area, I can improve my ability to provide more effective assistance in my users' goals and aspirations while continuously adapting to their evolving needs and challenges.

