  📤 → User: Based on the search results, here are some key limitations of dot-product attention in transformer models:

1. Dot-product attention calculates attention scores by taking the dot product of the query matrix (Q) with the key matrix (K), followed by a softmax function to obtain the attention weights. This approach is computationally efficient as it can be computed in parallel, solving the existing recursive neural network bottleneck.

2. However, dot-product attention struggles to capture nonlinear relationships between queries and keys, especially when they are vectors of different lengths. This limitation can lead to suboptimal attention weights and reduced model performance.

3. Another limitation of dot-product attention is its sensitivity to the scaling factor. The attention scores are scaled by dividing by the square root of the dimension of the key matrix (sqrt(d_k)). If the scaling factor is not chosen appropriately, it can affect the attention scores and the overall model performance.

4. Dot-product attention also assumes that the relationship between queries and keys is symmetric, which may not always be the case in certain tasks or domains. This limitation can lead to suboptimal attention weights and reduced model performance.

To overcome these limitations, researchers have proposed alternative attention mechanisms such as Sigmoid attention, ReLU attention, and Neural attention, which can capture nonlinear relationships and provide more expressive attention weights. These alternative attention mechanisms can improve the performance of transformer models in various tasks and domains.

